          <td bgcolor="#BF003F" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
<tr><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="98%"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/toptab.gif" width="98" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="22">&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> Making Your Article the Best It Can Be<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=1805'>Kenneth "Ken B" Bradford</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=1805&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> June 30, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> The halcyon days of Decktech&#39;s Star Wars CCG side...anyone remember those?<br><br>Recently I got *ahem* taken to task for DARING to review someone&#39;s one paragraph &quot;article&quot; with one star (which was in fact a rant having nothing to do with Star Wars CCG itself).  This just left me scratching my head.  Should I consider this one-paragraph masterpiece an ARTICLE, and rate it five stars?  Should I do it even if I agree with his position?<br><br>There is hope for this side of the site, though.  Christopher Simmon&#39;s &quot;Knowing Your Meta&quot; is a great article and has justifiably been number one for awhile now.  The same can be said for Joshua &quot;Stormcrow&quot; Grace and his Virtual Philosophy article.  In fact, if you want to write an article on Star Wars CCG for Decktech, these are great articles to at least mold your efforts after.<br><br>So here&#39;s a quick rundown on how to avoid the dreaded &#39;one-star&#39; reviews for your articles and in turn how you can continue to make Decktech THE premiere resource for Star Wars CCG players.<br><br><b>#1:  Make your Article About Star Wars CCG.</b><br><br>Sounds simple, right?  I mean, after all, that IS why we have the different sections of Decktech cordoned off from one another with separate article sections for each.  When someone opens an article in the Lord of the Rings section, they expect to actually <i>be about Lord of the Rings.</i>  Why should it be any different here?<br><br>Now there&#39;s a LOT of leeway in that topic.  You can cover playstyles.  Deck choices.  Card evaluations.  Combos.  General Strategy.  Tips on bluffing or card tracking.  Heck, I don&#39;t even mind fantasy cards--put PLEASE, if you&#39;re going to submit those...give them a little thought first, run them by some friends.  If you submit fantasy card articles and they&#39;re broken or wouldn&#39;t work properly, don&#39;t be surprised if your article gets HAMMERED.<br><br><b>#2:  SPELL AND GRAMMAR CHECK:</b><br><br>You can have the most compelling article known to man.   Maybe you&#39;ve discovered the world&#39;s strongest combo or why a certain card needs special attention for deckbuilding.  But when it comes out like this:<br><br><i>i think your bound to find uses for compputer interfvace(v)  its hella tedch in fact u shuld put it in all ur decks</i><br><br>Quickly any knowledge you hope to convey to someone else will be lost in the sea of typos, bad grammar, or &quot;l33t&quot; talk.  Many people will in fact soon tune out your message and focus on these mistakes to exclusion, which will certainly harm the review scores they&#39;re going to give you.  You may type it up in Notepad, but run it through Word too on your way to the &quot;submit It!&quot; button.  Content is king, but presentation goes a LONG way.<br><br><b>#3:  No Matter How Angry You Are, Resist the Urge to Rant or Whine</b><br><br>You may feel that Walkers are the strongest deck ever and are perhaps TOO strong.  So after getting thrashed by them at the Saturday tourny, you fire up your PC and unleash a torrent of an &quot;article&quot; tearing down Walkers.  You express rage, frustration, and an almost irrational pleading for something to be done about them.  You&#39;re satisfied with your efforts until the low ratings start coming in.  &quot;Idiots!&quot; you think.  &quot;My position is correct!  How can they rate me badly?!&quot;<br><br><br />
Unfortunately it&#39;s easy for a message to get lost somewhere in the middle of your diatribe.  Like the grammar and spelling mistakes, eventually the whining will overcome your message and people will get turned off by it.<br><br>You want to make your case?  Do it rationally, and with facts.  Resist the urge to rant and rave, no matter how angry you are.  If you find this impossible, take a quick jog or something and come back to your article then.  You&#39;ll catch more flies with honey than vinegar.  Stupid cliched adage, but it&#39;s true!<br><br><b>4:  The Article Needs to Do Someone Else Some Good:</b><br><br>You know, someone could type up an article about how they once beat Legend of Zelda II on the NES in 9 hours in a non-stop gaming session.  But that knowledge doesn&#39;t do ANYONE else any good, y&#39;know?  Same goes for an irrational hatred for some member of Decktech....there&#39;s a reason why we have Buzz Boards here, where any Joe can grab a soapbox and let it fly.  In fact, that&#39;s what it&#39;s there for.<br><br>An article is different, though.  When people read an article they expect for it to have SOMETHING of value to them.  That is the purpose for writing them--to distribute knowledge!  When your average Decktecher reads an article that teaches him nothing, he or she tends to get a little angry, and unleashes the one-star rating.  The one-star means &quot;This Article Wasted My Time!&quot;  And if someone doesn&#39;t take at least some small something from an article that he didn&#39;t come in there with, that&#39;s going to be their EXACT reaction.<br><br>Can you blame them?  Not every article has to be an English masterpiece, but it at LEAST should possess something of value to someone other than the writer.<br><br><b>#5:  Check Your Facts.</b><br><br>So you want to do an article about Hidden Base.  You toil over that article for hours and submit it....but in your haste you mention that X-Wing Cannons can target Bossk in Bus.<br><br>Now, this may not be the proper reaction but to a long-time veteran of Star Wars CCG, this misinformation can be jarring and you&#39;d better believe once they spot this mistake their perception of your article has already decreased dramatically.<br><br>And not just old-timers;  there are those on Decktech who just love to find these errors and smash your articles to pieces just for having them.  Should you get mad?  Well, yeah, this sort of thing IS harsh--after all, who doesn&#39;t make mistakes?  But even better--why not show &#39;em by taking the extra few minutes to research any fact you&#39;re not 100% sure about.  This includes card text, deploy costs, card interactions, you name it.  If you have to think about it, take a few extra seconds and look it up.  Nitpickers will by stymied and have to move on to the next schmo&#39;s article to find those mistakes, and your message will resonate better with long-time players.  Even if they already know everything you&#39;re sharing with them, they&#39;ll be a LOT more positive on their review if you hit all the factual nails on the head.<br><br><b>.#6  Even If You Follow All These Rules, You&#39;ll Still Get Bad Reviews</b><br><br>I&#39;ve busted my butt on some of my articles sometimes to still get stellar reviews like &quot;yo! mamma&quot; (one-star, natch) and &quot;no good compare to other articals--you owe me jeff&quot;.  Now I never did find out who Jeff was, or why someone would want to do him a favor...I once deduced it was Brian Hunter, whose article leapfrogged mine after that bad rating (I&#39;ll get you, you evil hippie!  :))<br><br>There&#39;s two things you can do:  you can go off on the person giving you the bad rating, for one.  This will make you feel tons better initially.  Until, of course, that same person turns around and rips apart all of your old articles....and then they wait with baited breath for your NEXT article, so they can rip that as well.  You see, they&#39;ve found a &quot;live one&quot;, someone who&#39;s skin they can get under with a meaningless review.  It&#39;s like the spammer who sends out email messages saying &quot;Click here to unsubscribe.&quot;  If you fall for that, BAM!  They&#39;ve got you.  Except instead of a spammer you find yourself at the mercy of some loser who is powerless in real life and turns to Decktech for his life&#39;s only empowerment.  Yikes.<br><br>Or, the better tact is to ignore them completely.  Then everyone who rates your article <i>properly</i> will also get to see in passing what an idiot the person who rated your article badly is.  Plus, since they couldn&#39;t rile you up, they&#39;ll move on and hopefully leave you alone.  Just don&#39;t play the &quot;troll&quot; game, and you&#39;ll be fine.<br><br><br>So there you have it!  If I&#39;ve offended you before or given you a bad rating on something, I won&#39;t be upset if you rate this badly.  I hope, rather, that you find something in here that helps you make a good article that has worth to your fellow Decktechers, and in turn Decktech continues to be the PREMIERE Star Wars (and heck, gaming in general) location for discussing this great game.  So good luck--and lose one from Visage, punk!<br><br>;))<br><br><br>Ken Bradford<br>Decktech Admin<br>Doin&#39; the Decktech thing since 1999! <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/starwarsccg/articles/articles.php?id=5691&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/starwarsccg/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/starwarsccg/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></td></tr></table>
